  "prompt": "Do consumer electronics have a shelf life?",
  "response": "Yes, consumer electronics do have a shelf life, though it varies depending on the type of device and its components. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Battery-powered devices\n- Batteries degrade over time, even when not in use\n- Lithium-ion batteries typically last 2-3 years before significant capacity loss\n- Unused batteries can lose charge and performance\n\n2. Electronic components\n- Capacitors and other internal parts can deteriorate\n- Semiconductors and circuit boards can degrade due to environmental factors\n- Typical useful life is 3-7 years for most consumer electronics\n\n3. Factors affecting shelf life\n- Temperature and humidity\n- Storage conditions\n- Quality of manufacturing\n- Original component quality\n\n4. Specific device examples\n- Smartphones: 2-5 years of optimal performance\n- Laptops: 3-5 years\n- TVs: 7-10 years\n- Cameras: 5-10 years\n- Gaming consoles: 5-7 years\n\n5. Storage recommendations\n- Store in cool, dry places\n- Keep away from direct sunlight\n- Avoid extreme temperatures\n- Periodically charge battery-powered devices\n\nWhile devices may physically last longer, their technological relevance and performance can decline more quickly.",
